ick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of   Shanahan  .","shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Seanáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Seanán</i>’, a personal name based on a pet form of <i>seán</i> ‘old’. This Irish surname became established in Scotland in the 14th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Shanahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamonn, Aidan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam, Marypat, Siobhan.","Irish (Tipperary and Limerick): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Seanacháin</b> or <b>Mac Seanacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Seanachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Seanach</i>, a personal name from <i>sean</i> ‘ancient, old’."]},{"name":"Synan","meanings":["Irish (County Cork): according to Woulfe, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sionáin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Seanáin</b> (see   Shannon  )."]}]},{"name":"Cassey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a North American name bestowed in honour of the American engine driver and folk hero ‘Casey’  Jones  (  1863–1900 ), who saved the lives of passengers on the ‘Cannonball Express’ at the expense of his own. He was baptized  Johnathan Luther Jones  in Cayce, Kentucky, and acquired his nickname from his birthplace. As a girl's name it is a variant of   Cassie .  In recent decades it has become equally popular in Britain, particularly as a name for girls. In part, this may reflect a transferred use of the Irish surname, a reduced Anglicized form of <i>Ó Cahasaigh</i> ‘descendant of Cathasach’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kacie","meanings":["Originally a North American name bestowed in honour of the American engine driver and folk hero ‘Casey’  Jones  (  1863–1900 ), who saved the lives of passengers on the ‘Cannonball Express’ at the expense of his own. He was baptized  Johnathan Luther Jones  in Cayce, Kentucky, and acquired his nickname from his birthplace. As a girl's name it is a variant of   Cassie .  In recent decades it has become equally popular in Britain, particularly as a name for girls. In part, this may reflect a transferred use of the Irish surname, a reduced Anglicized form of <i>Ó Cahasaigh</i> ‘descendant of Cathasach’."]},{"name":"Casy","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Casey ."]},{"name":"Kacey","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Casey ."]},{"name":"Kasey","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Casey ."]},{"name":"Kaci","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Casey ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cassey Shannon was born in 1443, in Rathdown, County Wicklow, Ireland, her father, William Shannon, was 23 and her mother, Rosetta Fisher, was 21. She married John Rowland I in 1460, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1489, in Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1443–1489":"1443–1489","1440–1466":"1440–1466","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1423–Female":"1423–Surnud","1489":"1489","1423":"1423","1466":"1466","1443":"1443","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","Rathdown, County Wicklow, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathdown, County Wicklow, Iirimaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1443–1489":"1443–1489","1440–1466":"1440–1466","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1423–Female":"1423–Kuollut","1489":"1489","1423":"1423","1466":"1466","1443":"1443","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","Rathdown, County Wicklow, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathdown, County Wicklow, Irlanti","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1443–1489":"1443–1489","1440–1466":"1440–1466","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1420–Male":"1420–Décédé","1423–Female":"1423–Décéd